        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Requested sensitivity/bandpass accuracy: 
Uranus has an average brightness of 1.25 Jy per 0.4" beam in Band 7. We request a sensitivity of 2.5 mJy/beam at a spectral resolution of 1129 kHz, which translates into 1 hour on source for a total time of 2.1 hours. Our sensitivity is limited by ALMA's bandpass accuracy of 1 part in 500; we have designed our science goals to be achievable within this limitation. At this sensitivity, we will 1) improve the 3 sigma HCN detection limit by a factor of 10 (Fig. 2) . This improved detection limit is sufficiently low to allow for detection of HCN formed from N2 of internal origin, as well as HCN that may be deposited by a comet impact. 2) Measure the vertical CO profile; we will be able to distinguish between the empirical vertically uniform and stratosphere-only CO profiles used by previous authors at the 4 sigma level (Fig. 1). 3) Map latitudinal variations in the CO abundance of 50% or more, in order to determine the mechanism for supplying CO to Uranus' stratosphere (Fig. 3, center).

We note that while the sensitivity requirements have been framed in reference to the detection of HCN, the requested sensitivity has been used to calculate our ability to achieve all of the science goals outlined above and in the Science Case.

Imaging requirements:
We request a resolution of 0.4"; this resolution corresponds to 15 degrees or about 5500 km at disk center on Uranus. This spatial scale is relevant to observing horizontal CO and HCN variations due to global circulation patterns, as have been observed at cm wavelengths and in the visible; as well as to detecting variations due to localized infall, such as due to a cometary impact. Furthermore, the CO and HCN line contrasts are greater towards Uranus' limb; by resolving the planet we will increase our ability to detect HCN on Uranus for the first time (see Fig. 2).

Correlator setup:
Since CO lines are pressure-broadened to a width of several GHz, we will use ALMA's 1875 MHz band mode to observe the CO line. The contributions from different levels of the atmosphere to different parts of the CO line are shown in Fig. 1, emphasizing the need to observe as much of the CO line shape as possible. We cannot observe both wings of the CO (3-2) line with a single correlator setup, so we have chosen to observe the low frequency wing of CO out to a distance of 3.3 GHz from line center, and the high frequency wing out only to a distance of 500 MHz. Experience observing Neptune at CARMA with a similar setup gives us confidence that an asymmetric frequency coverage will be sufficient to model the CO altitude profile. We will average by a factor of 2 (1.129 MHz resolution) in the spectral window containing the line core, which will give us 3 channels across the CO emission peak at disk center. Near the limb, where Doppler broadening has a greater effect, we will have 8 channels across the line core. In the spectral window that captures the CO line wings, we are interested in the line shape; however, this shape varies less quickly at larger offsets from line center (Fig 1). We will average 16 channels for a resolution of 7.813 MHz.

We will also observe the HCN emission core with an 1875 MHz spectral window with an averaging factor of 2, for a resolution of 1.129 MHz. Like for CO, we will have 3 channels in the line core at disk center, and 8 channels in the core near the limb.  We elect to use a wide bandwidth mode (1875 MHz) because the spectral resolution is sufficient in this mode. This also allows us to observe continuum emission from Uranus, which is itself an interesting science target. We place the final spectral window in the lowest resolution FDM mode at 357 GHz to observe the shape of the submillimeter continuum of Uranus.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
