    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>In equilibrium, the molecules carbon monoxide (CO) and hydrogen cyanide (HCN) are confined to the warm interiors of the giant planets. Their presence in the stratosphere, therefore, indicates disequilibrium processes: either rapid vertical transport from deeper levels where the molecules are thermodynamically stable, or production in the stratosphere as a result of photochemistry and/or infall. We will observe the CO (3-2) and HCN (4-3) rotation lines on Uranus. With a noise rms of 2.5 mJy/beam and resolution of 0.4", we will 1) determine the vertical profile of CO;  2) improve the HCN detection limit on Uranus by a factor of 10; and 3) measure the latitudinal distribution of CO and HCN in the stratosphere of Uranus for the first time. These observations will provide a wealth of information on the atmospheric dynamics and internal composition of Uranus, as well as the environment in the outer Solar System. </prp:abstract>
